Force byte arithmetic for fiber machine-stack size in cont.c

ALLOC_N(VALUE, n) and MEMCPY(dest, src, VALUE, n) both expand to
sizeof(VALUE) * n bytes. Ruby 1.9's cont_save_machine_stack and
fiber_setcontext compute n as `start - end` where start and end are
VALUE *. The C standard makes that pointer subtraction undefined when
the two pointers don't point into the same array; here `start` and
`end` are taken from different stack frames (RUBY_INIT_STACK and
rb_gc_set_stack_end respectively).

Under the iOS sim arm64 toolchain (clang 21) the compiled code emits
asymmetric size handling: ALLOC_N gets the truncated element count
(byte_diff >> 3) but the MEMCPY size is folded to the raw byte_diff
(no shift). Result: malloc returns N*8 bytes, memcpy writes
N*8 + (byte_diff & 7) bytes - a tiny heap-buffer-overflow that ASan
flags directly and that xzone_malloc detects later as freelist
corruption (which surfaces as different-looking crashes deeper in
the engine: vorbis decode, font lookups, etc).

Casting through char * forces the compiler to treat the subtraction
as integer math and to apply the >> 3 / * 8 round-trip consistently
to both call sites. We round DOWN, dropping at most 7 bytes from the
top of the saved stack region; that loss is a few bytes of
compiler-padding above the highest live VALUE-aligned slot, never a
live root.

Same hunk applied to the FIBER_USE_NATIVE branch in fiber_setcontext
where the symmetric `oldfib->cont.machine_stack_size = ...`
assignment lives, so a future config that flips FIBER_USE_NATIVE on
doesn't reintroduce the bug there.

diff --git a/cont.c b/cont.c
--- a/cont.c
+++ b/cont.c
@@ -346,11 +346,15 @@ cont_save_machine_stack(rb_thread_t *th, rb_context_t *cont)
 #endif
 
     if (th->machine_stack_start > th->machine_stack_end) {
-	size = cont->machine_stack_size = th->machine_stack_start - th->machine_stack_end;
+	size = cont->machine_stack_size =
+	    ((char *)th->machine_stack_start - (char *)th->machine_stack_end) /
+	    sizeof(VALUE);
 	cont->machine_stack_src = th->machine_stack_end;
     }
     else {
-	size = cont->machine_stack_size = th->machine_stack_end - th->machine_stack_start;
+	size = cont->machine_stack_size =
+	    ((char *)th->machine_stack_end - (char *)th->machine_stack_start) /
+	    sizeof(VALUE);
 	cont->machine_stack_src = th->machine_stack_start;
     }
 
@@ -635,11 +639,15 @@ fiber_setcontext(rb_fiber_t *newfib, rb_fiber_t *oldfib)
 	STACK_GROW_DIR_DETECTION;
 	SET_MACHINE_STACK_END(&th->machine_stack_end);
 	if (STACK_DIR_UPPER(0, 1)) {
-	    oldfib->cont.machine_stack_size = th->machine_stack_start - th->machine_stack_end;
+	    oldfib->cont.machine_stack_size =
+		((char *)th->machine_stack_start - (char *)th->machine_stack_end) /
+		sizeof(VALUE);
 	    oldfib->cont.machine_stack = th->machine_stack_end;
 	}
 	else {
-	    oldfib->cont.machine_stack_size = th->machine_stack_end - th->machine_stack_start;
+	    oldfib->cont.machine_stack_size =
+		((char *)th->machine_stack_end - (char *)th->machine_stack_start) /
+		sizeof(VALUE);
 	    oldfib->cont.machine_stack = th->machine_stack_start;
 	}
     }
